entry.title: GPU process and renderer consuming 70% CPU, no clue given what tab is responsible
entry.content:
Chrome Version : 123.0.0.0 OS Version : URLs (if applicable) : Other browsers tested: Add OK or FAIL, along with the version, after other browsers where you have tested this issue: Safari: Firefox: Edge:
What steps will reproduce the problem? (1) Open the task manager
What is the expected result? What happens instead of that? See the screenshot: between the "GPU process" and "Renderer" (whatever that is) combined, are consuming about 70% CPU, but no tab in particular indicates a high CPU consumption. Usually, when the GPU process has high CPU consumption, there's also one or more tabs that do: I'm not sure if that is a coincidence, but I've always assumed that that means that a tab is consuming a lot of CPU in doing GPU/rendering stuff and you indicate that by attributing the consumption to both the particular tab and the GPU process, or something like that. One way or another, if the renderer and/or the GPU process, whatever they are, are consuming a lot of GPU, I expect to be able to tell what tab is the culprit. If there is no tab requiring such abnormal CPU consumption, then that would be a bug in itself. If there is one or more tabs in particular that are responsible, directly or indirectly, for such abnormal CPU consumption, you must tell me which ones, one way or another.
Please provide any additional information below. Attach a screenshot if possible.
UserAgentString: Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/123.0.0.0 Safari/537.36
For graphics-related bugs, please copy/paste the contents of the about:gpu page at the end of this report.

entry.title: [css-anchor-position] `anchor-size()` should fallback to `auto`, not zero
entry.content:
CSSWG added the following resolution(s):
> * `RESOLVED: if an anchor-size can't resolve and doesn't have a fallback, then it is ICVT` > * `RESOLVED: if an anchor() can't resolve and doesn't have a fallback, then it is ICVT`
in https://github.com/w3c/csswg-drafts/issues/10005#issuecomment-2047966753
This bug was filed by the Spec Resolution Github Bot. This [doc](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1h3-Il_KusVrvVfC86yYhNtTWz5fEoBe3FraCOcZZLyU/edit) briefly describes the process. Please reach out to chrishtr@chromium.org for questions.

entry.title: Update fakebox text and icons to be accessible in all themes and contrast levels
entry.content:
Observed: Monochrome theme + when contrast control is set to High, the omnibox text and icons do not render correctly. Expected: use onSurface for both text and icons.
Previously text/icons were mapped to onPrimaryContainer but it does not match the backgroundg pairing of Primary @ %. To avoid changing the omnibox color and potentially running an additional experiment, we will update the text to be onSurface instead.
Color contrast deck for reference: https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1Dt1Zk07B6DMy5LML7tpQsQh27sXWDJQ9CeLz7Axwg54/edit#slide=id.p

entry.title: Regression: Ongoing scroll-snap causes all scroll gestures to be captured by scroll-snap container
entry.content:
# Steps to reproduce the problem 1. Scroll vertically the scroll-snap container (middle) 2. Before the end of the snap, try to scroll vertically either the normal scroll container (left) or the body (right) 3. Observe that no scroll is occurring in the normal scroll container or the body, instead the scroll-snap container captures the gesture and gets scrolled
# Problem Description Test case: https://output.jsbin.com/nawoqerulo
Scroll-snap containers seem to capture all scroll gestures as long as scroll they have ongoing scroll. As a result, if you scroll inside of scroll-snap container, and then try to scroll the page or another scroll-snap container while the scroll is not completely settled, the initial scroll-snap container will get scrolled instead. In my tests, this affects both mouse and touch-based scrolling.
This is a rather severe bug as it degrades significantly the experience with most usage of scroll-snap. I believe it was introduced recently, in one of the last 3 versions.
# Summary Regression: Ongoing scroll-snap causes all scroll gestures to be captured by scroll-snap container
# Custom Questions #### Which component does this fall under? Blink>Scroll
#### Does this work in other browsers? Yes - This is just a Chrome problem
# Additional Data Category: API \ Chrome Channel: Stable \ Regression: Yes

entry.title: Modernize support for is_asan on Android
entry.content:
Right now `is_asan=true` is hard to use on Android because:
1) It [does not work for x64](https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:tools/android/asan/third_party/BUILD.gn;drc=ed42716683ab56e61ef971ac50143c5f952b75b9;l=9) 2) It uses the device-breaking `asan_device_setup` method instead of the newer `wrap.sh` method, as described [here](https://github.com/google/sanitizers/wiki/AddressSanitizerOnAndroid/01f8df1ac1a447a8475cdfcb03e8b13140042dbd#running)

entry.title: [ios] Only enable sync when signing in identity from UI where explicitly needed in testing
entry.content:
Suggestion for a cleanup task to make the usage of helpers for signing in in egtests less confusing, post UNO
Since UNO, most test cases that sign-in and need account data activated don't need Sync at all, except when a test covers the legacy Sync feature.
This means that helper methods like `+[SigninEarlGreyUI signinWithFakeIdentity:(FakeSystemIdentity*)fakeIdentity]` [1] should not enable sync by default (the method use enableSync:YES)
Or maybe just changing the enableSync parameter for throughUI name will be sufficient, as when enableSync is NO, sign-in is done directly through the authentication flow instead of the sign-in prompt.
My understanding is that some tests want to test the sign-in prompt itself, where the sign-in prompt UI should be displayed, and the currently use enableSync:YES which is confusing (do they test sync or just use the sign-in prompt UI?).
But still, signing in through the UI should only be done when necessary where using `[SigninEarlGrey signinWithFakeIdentity:[FakeSystemIdentity fakeIdentity1]];` is sufficient (no UI at all). There might be some egtest refactoring to be done here. This has the potential of reducing the runtime of these tests.
There is also `-[ChromeEarlGrey waitForSyncEngineInitialized]`[2] that can be replaced in both sign-in flows (with and without Sync), by -waitForSyncTransportStateActiveWithTimeout which really waits on account data or Sync to be ready.
--- [1]: https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:ios/chrome/browser/ui/authentication/signin_earl_grey_ui_test_util.mm;l=94;drc=946e68c02af4db2e67476042dece1c08ab83ea11 [2]: https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:ios/chrome/browser/ui/authentication/signin_earl_grey_ui_test_util.mm;l=147;drc=946e68c02af4db2e67476042dece1c08ab83ea11

entry.title: formFactors value is lost after overwriting user agent data via CDP
entry.content:
# Steps to reproduce the problem 1. run chrome with the remote-debugging-port command line switch: google-chrome-beta --remote-debugging-port=0 2. check user agent data in console tab: await navigator.userAgentData.getHighEntropyValues(["mobile","architecture","model","platform","platformVersion","formFactors"]) 3. open "Protocol monitor" in devtools 4. run Emulation.setUserAgentOverride in protocol monitor tab: {"command":"Emulation.setUserAgentOverride","parameters":{"userAgent":"Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/125.0.0.0 Safari/537.36","userAgentMetadata":{"platform":"Linux","platformVersion":"5.15.0","architecture":"x86","model":"","mobile":false}}} 5. check user agent data again in console tab: await navigator.userAgentData.getHighEntropyValues(["mobile","architecture","model","platform","platformVersion","formFactors"])
# Problem Description After overwriting user agent data via CDP with Emulation.setUserAgentOverride "formFactors" value is lost and returned as empty string. This value should remain after overwrite as currently it is not possible to overwrite it like the rest of the user agent data values: https://chromedevtools.github.io/devtools-protocol/tot/Emulation/#type-UserAgentMetadata
The same thing happens with Sec-CH-UA-Form-Factors header.
# Additional Comments I have attached a screen recording as well.
# Summary formFactors value is lost after overwriting user agent data via CDP
# Additional Data Category: Developer Tools \ Chrome Channel: Beta \ Regression: N/A

entry.title: Accessibility issue in "Use chromium by default" view
entry.content:
Start Chrome on iOS with a recent install, so that you get "Use chromium by default". Activate voice over. Navigate down.
Youll get "1" as an entry separate from "Open settings". And similar for the other numbers. Either they should not be read at all, or they should be part of the same accessibility text. There is no reason for them to request an extra move from the user.
